{"title_page": "The Countess Died of Laughter", "text_new": "{{short description|1973 film by Franz Antel}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Countess Died of Laughter\n| image          = File:Tolles toechterlein.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Franz Antel]]\n| producer       = Franz Antel<br>[[Carl Szokoll]]\n| writer         = Kurt Nachmann<br>Vittoria Vigorelli\n| based on       = \n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Gabriele Tinti (actor)|Gabriele Tinti]]<br>[[Teri Tordai]]\n| music          = [[Stelvio Cipriani]]\n| cinematography = [[Siegfried Hold]]\t\t\n| editing        = [[Femi Benussi ]]\n| studio = Cinemar <br> Neue Delta Filmproduktion\n| distributor    = [[Constantin Film]] ([[West Germany]])\n| released       = 11 April 1973 (Italy)<br>19 April 1973 (West Germany) \t\n| runtime        = 86 minutes\n| country        = [[Austria]]<br>[[Italy]]\n| language       = [[German language|German]]/[[Italian language|Italian]]\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''The Countess Died of Laughter''''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Frau Wirtins tolle T\u00f6chterlein'', [[Italian language|Italian]]: ''Leva lo diavolo tuo dal... convento'') is a 1973 Austrian-Italian [[sex comedy]] film directed by [[Franz Antel]]. It is the final entry in Franz Antel's series ''[[The Sweet Sins of Sexy Susan|Frau Wirtin]]'' and incorporates a great deal of archive footage from earlier films.\n\n==Plot==\nSusanne Delberg ([[Teri Tordai]] as Terry Torday) who has become Countess S\u00fcderland dies under absurd circumstances. It is revealed that Susanne had a daughter, the heiress to her inheritance but her identity is obscure, although it is known that she has been living in a convent. The handsome [[executor]] Vincent van der Straten ([[Gabriele Tinti (actor)|Gabriele Tinti]]) is assigned for the task. There are five possible candidates: Fran\u00e7oise (Maja Hoppe), Clarissa ([[Femi Benussi]] as Femy Benussi), Susanne ([[Sonja Jeannine]]), Piroschka (Marika Mindzenthy), and Anselma (Alena Penz). Van der Straten decides to stay at the convent to find the real heiress but things soon prove to be difficult for him since all the candidates happen to be as raunchy as late Susanne.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Teri Tordai]] as Susanne Delberg \n* [[Gabriele Tinti (actor)|Gabriele Tinti ]] as Vincent van der Straaten \n* [[Femi Benussi ]] as Clarissa\n* [[Christina Losta ]] as Francoise \n* [[Marika Mindzenthy ]] as Piroschka \n* [[Alena Penz ]] as Anselma \n* [[Sonja Jeannine]] as Susanne \n* [[Margot Hielscher ]] as Reverend Mother \n* [[Paul L\u00f6winger ]] as Antonius \n* [[Kurt Gro\u00dfkurth]] as Monk \n* [[Jacques Herlin ]] as Monsieur Dulac \n* [[Hans Terofal ]] as Jussuf \n* [[Franz Muxeneder ]] as Farmer \n* [[Galliano Sbarra ]] as Governatore \n* [[Joanna Jung ]] as Anna \n* [[Maja Hoppe ]] as Telltale Girl \n* [[Erich Padalewski ]] as Piroschka's Lover \n* [[Dolores Schmidinger ]] as Nun \n* [[Raoul Retzer]] as Osmin \n* [[Raimund Folkert]] as Florian \n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB title|0070076|Frau Wirtins tolle T\u00f6chterlein}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Countess Died of Laughter, The}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Commedia sexy all'italiana]]\n[[Category:Austrian films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:German-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Franz Antel]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Stelvio Cipriani]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1810s]]\n[[Category:Films set in Germany]]\n[[Category:Austrian sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Austrian multilingual films]]\n[[Category:Italian multilingual films]]\n[[Category:1970s multilingual films]]\n[[Category:German historical comedy films]]\n[[Category:Italian historical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s historical comedy films]]\n[[Category:Constantin Film films]]\n\n{{erotic-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1973 film by Franz Antel}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Countess Died of Laughter\n| image          = File:Tolles toechterlein.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Franz Antel]]\n| producer       = Franz Antel<br>[[Carl Szokoll]]\n| writer         = Kurt Nachmann<br>Vittoria Vigorelli\n| based on       = \n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Gabriele Tinti (actor)|Gabriele Tinti]]<br>[[Teri Tordai]]\n| music          = [[Stelvio Cipriani]]\n| cinematography = [[Siegfried Hold]]\t\t\n| editing        = [[Femi Benussi ]]\n| studio = Cinemar <br> Neue Delta Filmproduktion\n| distributor    = [[Constantin Film]] ([[West Germany]])\n| released       = 11 April 1973 (Italy)<br>19 April 1973 (West Germany) \t\n| runtime        = 86 minutes\n| country        = [[Austria]]<br>[[Italy]]\n| language       = [[German language|German]]/[[Italian language|Italian]]\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''The Countess Died of Laughter''''' ([[German language|German]]: ''Frau Wirtins tolle T\u00f6chterlein'', [[Italian language|Italian]]: ''Leva lo diavolo tuo dal... convento'') is a 1973 Austrian-Italian [[sex comedy]] film directed by [[Franz Antel]]. It is the final entry in Franz Antel's series ''[[The Sweet Sins of Sexy Susan|Frau Wirtin]]'' and incorporates a great deal of archive footage from earlier films.\n\n==Plot==\nSusanne Delberg ([[Teri Tordai]] as Terry Torday) who has become Countess S\u00fcderland dies under absurd circumstances. It is revealed that Susanne had a daughter, the heiress to her inheritance but her identity is obscure, although it is known that she has been living in a convent. The handsome [[executor]] Vincent van der Straten ([[Gabriele Tinti (actor)|Gabriele Tinti]]) is assigned for the task. There are five possible candidates: Fran\u00e7oise (Maja Hoppe), Clarissa ([[Femi Benussi]] as Femy Benussi), Susanne ([[Sonja Jeannine]]), Piroschka (Marika Mindzenthy), and Anselma (Alena Penz). Van der Straten decides to stay at the convent to find the real heiress but things soon prove to be difficult for him since all the candidates happen to be as raunchy as late Susanne.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Teri Tordai]] as Susanne Delberg \n* [[Gabriele Tinti ]] as Vincent van der Straaten \n* [[Femi Benussi ]] as Clarissa\n* [[Christina Losta ]] as Francoise \n* [[Marika Mindzenthy ]] as Piroschka \n* [[Alena Penz ]] as Anselma \n* [[Sonja Jeannine]] as Susanne \n* [[Margot Hielscher ]] as Reverend Mother \n* [[Paul L\u00f6winger ]] as Antonius \n* [[Kurt Gro\u00dfkurth]] as Monk \n* [[Jacques Herlin ]] as Monsieur Dulac \n* [[Hans Terofal ]] as Jussuf \n* [[Franz Muxeneder ]] as Farmer \n* [[Galliano Sbarra ]] as Governatore \n* [[Joanna Jung ]] as Anna \n* [[Maja Hoppe ]] as Telltale Girl \n* [[Erich Padalewski ]] as Piroschka's Lover \n* [[Dolores Schmidinger ]] as Nun \n* [[Raoul Retzer]] as Osmin \n* [[Raimund Folkert]] as Florian \n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB title|0070076|Frau Wirtins tolle T\u00f6chterlein}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Countess Died of Laughter, The}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Commedia sexy all'italiana]]\n[[Category:Austrian films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:German-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Franz Antel]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Stelvio Cipriani]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1810s]]\n[[Category:Films set in Germany]]\n[[Category:Austrian sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Austrian multilingual films]]\n[[Category:Italian multilingual films]]\n[[Category:1970s multilingual films]]\n[[Category:German historical comedy films]]\n[[Category:Italian historical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s historical comedy films]]\n[[Category:Constantin Film films]]\n\n{{erotic-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGabriele Tinti(link changed toGabriele Tinti (actor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Countess_Died_of_Laughter"}
{"title_page": "Henry Hildebrand", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=January 2016}}\n'''Henry Hildebrand''' (November 16, 1911 \u2013 February 7, 2006) is most known for being the founding principal (later called president) of [[Briercrest Bible Institute]] for 42 years; the school is now known as [[Briercrest Family of Schools]] or [[Briercrest College and Seminary]].\n\n==History==\nBorn in 1911, Henry Hildebrand immigrated to Canada with his parents Peter and Anna, and the rest of their family in 1925 from southern Russia (Ukraine) for political reasons. They settled near [[Winkler, Manitoba]].  At age 14, Hildebrand was converted at a [[Canadian Sunday School Mission]] summer camp.\n\nIn 1929 Hildebrand enrolled in Winnipeg Bible Institute (now known as [[Providence University College and Theological Seminary]]), where he earned an undergraduate degree and completed a year of post-graduate studies.  It was at this time he met [[Inger Soyland]]. A Norwegian by descent, Inger had come to Canada with a cousin to visit her aunt, but her return to Norway was cancelled when the Depression struck.\n\nIn 1935 he accepted an invitation to come to the small town of [[Briercrest, Saskatchewan]], to lead the Briercrest Gospel Assembly. That same year Briercrest Bible Institute was founded. In 1946 the institute moved to [[Caronport, Saskatchewan]], and a Christian high school was created. The Bible institute grew to become one of Canada's largest Christian post-secondary schools (now known as Briercrest College and Seminary).\n\nHildebrand married [[Inger Soyland]] on August 12, 1937, and brought his new bride to Briercrest.  Their family grew to include five children, Marcia, Evelyn, David, Paul, and Glen.\n\nAfter his retirement in 1977, Hildebrand served as chancellor until 1990, and chancellor emeritus until his death. He and Inger moved from Caronport in 1992, but remained very involved in the ministry of Briercrest.\n\nOn October 24, 1979, Hildebrand was invested by Governor-General Edward Schreyer with membership in the nation's highest civil honour, the Order of Canada, for his leadership in Christian education through Briercrest and the impact of his life upon Canadian youth and society.\n\n==Education==\n    '''Winnipeg Bible Institute'''\n    1930-32\u2013Diploma\n    1932-33\u2013Post-graduate\n\n    '''[[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]]'''\n    1949\n\n    '''Winona Lake School of Theology'''\n    1964\u2013BA (major in Bible)\n    1966\u2013MA\n\n==Recognition==\n*[[Order of Canada]] - October 24, 1979\n*Received the nation's highest civil honour at a ceremony at Government House, Ottawa\n*Hildebrand was invested by Governor-General [[Edward Schreyer]] with membership in the Order of Canada\n*Given in recognition of Dr. Hildebrand's lifelong work in Christian education through [[Briercrest Family of Schools]] and for the impact of his life upon Canadian youth and society.\n*Honorary doctorate (Doctor of Divinity) from [[Providence University College and Theological Seminary|Providence College]] in 1977.\n*Honorary doctorate (Doctor of Pedagogy) from [[Briercrest Bible College]] in 1992, as well as the Queen's Golden Jubilee Medal.\n\n==Church affiliation==\n\n    * Caronport Community Church\n    * Central Heights MB Church - Abbotsford, BC\n\n==Books published==\n    * In His Loving Service \u2013 Memoirs by Henry Hildebrand (published 1985)\n    * Contemporary Leadership Dynamics \u2013 Illustrations from Acts (published 1987)\n    * The Model of Servant Leadership \u2013 (published 1990)\n    * Living the Abounding Life\u2013Empowered by the Holy Spirit \u2013 (published 1996)\n    * Our Gracious and Loving Heavenly Father \u2013 Devotionals \u2013 Book 1 (published 1999)\n    * Our Gracious and Loving Heavenly Father \u2013 Devotionals \u2013 Book 2 (published 2000)\n    * Joyful Servants: A Biography of David and Jeannie Hildebrand \u2013 (published 2001)\n    * Our Gracious God and Loving Heavenly Father, Vols. 1, 2, 3, 4\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hildebrand, Henry}}\n[[Category:Canadian university and college chief executives]]\n[[Category:Wheaton College (Illinois) alumni]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=January 2016}}\n'''Henry Hildebrand''' (November 16, 1911 \u2013 February 7, 2006) is most known for being the founding principal (later called president) of [[Briercrest Bible Institute]] for 42 years; the school is now known as [[Briercrest Family of Schools]] or [[Briercrest College and Seminary]].\n\n==History==\nBorn in 1911, Henry Hildebrand immigrated to Canada with his parents Peter and Anna, and the rest of their family in 1925 from southern Russia (Ukraine) for political reasons. They settled near [[Winkler, Manitoba]].  At age 14, Hildebrand was converted at a [[Canadian Sunday School Mission]] summer camp.\n\nIn 1929 Hildebrand enrolled in Winnipeg Bible Institute (now known as [[Providence University College and Theological Seminary]]), where he earned an undergraduate degree and completed a year of post-graduate studies.  It was at this time he met [[Inger Soyland]]. A Norwegian by descent, Inger had come to Canada with a cousin to visit her aunt, but her return to Norway was cancelled when the Depression struck.\n\nIn 1935 he accepted an invitation to come to the small town of [[Briercrest, Saskatchewan]], to lead the Briercrest Gospel Assembly. That same year Briercrest Bible Institute was founded. In 1946 the institute moved to [[Caronport, Saskatchewan]], and a Christian high school was created. The Bible institute grew to become one of Canada\u2019s largest Christian post-secondary schools (now known as Briercrest College and Seminary).\n\nHildebrand married [[Inger Soyland]] on August 12, 1937, and brought his new bride to Briercrest.  Their family grew to include five children, Marcia, Evelyn, David, Paul, and Glen.\n\nAfter his retirement in 1977, Hildebrand served as chancellor until 1990, and chancellor emeritus until his death. He and Inger moved from Caronport in 1992, but remained very involved in the ministry of Briercrest.\n\nOn October 24, 1979, Dr. Hildebrand was invested by Governor-General Edward Schreyer with membership in the nation\u2019s highest civil honour, the Order of Canada, for his leadership in Christian education through Briercrest and the impact of his life upon Canadian youth and society.\n\n==Education==\n    '''Winnipeg Bible Institute'''\n    1930-32\u2013Diploma\n    1932-33\u2013Post-graduate\n\n    '''[[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]]'''\n    1949\n\n    '''Winona Lake School of Theology'''\n    1964\u2013BA (major in Bible)\n    1966\u2013MA\n\n==Recognition==\n*[[Order of Canada]] - October 24, 1979\n*Received the nation\u2019s highest civil honour at a ceremony at Government House, Ottawa\n*Dr. Hildebrand was invested by Governor-General [[Edward Schreyer]] with membership in the Order of Canada\n*Given in recognition of Dr. Hildebrand\u2019s lifelong work in Christian education through [[Briercrest Family of Schools]] and for the impact of his life upon Canadian youth and society.\n*Honorary Doctorate (Doctor of Divinity) from [[Providence University College and Theological Seminary|Providence College]] in 1977.\n*Honorary Doctorate (Doctor of Pedagogy) from [[Briercrest Bible College]] in 1992, as well as the Queen's Golden Jubilee Medal.\n\n==Church Affiliation==\n\n    * Caronport Community Church\n    * Central Heights MB Church - Abbotsford, BC\n\n==Books Published==\n    * In His Loving Service \u2013 Memoirs by Henry Hildebrand (published 1985)\n    * Contemporary Leadership Dynamics \u2013 Illustrations from Acts (published 1987)\n    * The Model of Servant Leadership \u2013 (published 1990)\n    * Living the Abounding Life\u2013Empowered by the Holy Spirit \u2013 (published 1996)\n    * Our Gracious and Loving Heavenly Father \u2013 Devotionals \u2013 Book 1 (published 1999)\n    * Our Gracious and Loving Heavenly Father \u2013 Devotionals \u2013 Book 2 (published 2000)\n    * Joyful Servants: A Biography of David and Jeannie Hildebrand \u2013 (published 2001)\n    * Our Gracious God and Loving Heavenly Father, Vols. 1, 2, 3, 4\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hildebrand, Henry}}\n[[Category:Canadian university and college chief executives]]\n[[Category:Wheaton College (Illinois) alumni]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, punct, use surname", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Hildebrand"}
{"title_page": "Soprano (singer)", "text_new": "{{Expand French|Soprano (rappeur)|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Soprano\n|background = solo_singer\n|image =Soprano 2011.jpg\n|caption = Soprano at \"SOS-Racisme\" concert on 14 July 2011\n|birth_name = Sa\u00efd M'Roumbaba\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|01|14|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Marseille]], France\n|genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n|occupation = Songwriter, singer\n|years_active = 1995\u2013present\n|associated_acts = [[Psy 4 de la Rime]]\n|website = {{URL|www.soprano-lesite.fr}}\n}}\n'''Sa\u00efd M'Roumbaba''' ({{IPA-fr|said \u025bm\u0281umbaba}}; born 14 January 1979 in [[Marseille]]), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Soprano''', is a French singer and rapper.<ref name=\"Gutierrez\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=soprano-p862366/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography: Soprano|last=Gutierrez|first=Evan C.|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref> He is a part of the rap group [[Psy 4 de la Rime]].<ref name=\"Birchmeier\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=psy-4-de-la-rime-p748789/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography: Psy 4 de la Rime|last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref> After leaving the group to make his first solo album he recorded his solo debut ''Puisqu'il Faut Vivre'' which made the [[European Top 100 Albums|''Billboard'' European Top 100]].<ref name=\"Gutierrez\" /> He returned in 2010 with a new solo album called ''La Colombe'', which included collaborations with numerous artists such as [[Indila]] and Amadou & Mariam. He has continued to work with Psy4 de la Rime: their third album, ''Les Cit\u00e9s d'Or'', was released in 2008, and their fourth album ''4eme Dimension'' came out in April 2013.\n\nOn 19 September 2019, Soprano entered at the [[Mus\u00e9e Gr\u00e9vin]]. His wax statue wears a hat signed by De Bornarel, a [[Karl Lagerfeld]] jacket and Aaron Jah Stone jewellery; the outfit is the one he wore at the [[NRJ Music Award|NRJ Music Awards]] 2018 ceremony.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sortiraparis.com/arts-culture/exposition/articles/198632-soprano-entre-au-musee-grevin|title=Soprano entre au Mus\u00e9e Gr\u00e9vin|website=www.sortiraparis.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref> \"We kept this outfit, we thought it mixed ''The Voice'', my career, the scene... it summed it up well\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr/provence-alpes-cote-d-azur/bouches-du-rhone/marseille/apres-maitre-gims-kendji-girac-mika-soprano-rentre-au-musee-grevin-1720865.html|title=Apr\u00e8s Ma\u00eetre Gims, Kendji Girac ou Mika, Soprano rentre au mus\u00e9e Gr\u00e9vin|website=France 3 Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref> he told [[France 3]].\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|Psy 4 de la Rime}}\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Units\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Certifications<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-certifications/|title=Les certifications|website=SNEP|language=fr-FR|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|FRA]]<br/><ref name=\"FRA\">{{cite web|url=http://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Soprano|title=Discographie Soprano|work=French Charts Portal|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br/>(Wa)]]<br/><ref name=\"WA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Soprano|title=Discographie Soprano|work=Belgium (Wallonia) Charts Portal|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Swiss Hitparade|SWI]]<br/><ref name=\"SWI\">{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Soprano|title=Discographie Soprano|work=Swiss Charts Portal|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[:fr:Puisqu'il faut vivre|Puisqu'il faut vivre]]''\n| \n* Released: 17 February 2007\n* Label: [[EMI]], Hostile Records, Street Skillz\n* Format: Digital download, CD\n| 2 || 14 || 26\n|\n|\n* FRA: Gold\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[:fr:La Colombe (album)|La Colombe]]''\n| \n* Released: 4 October 2010\n* Label: EMI, Hostile Records, Street Skillz\n* Format: Digital download, CD\n| 1 || 5 || 18\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n* FRA: 265,000+<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Soprano/news-92477.html|title=Clip de \"Ils nous connaissent pas\" : Soprano d\u00e9nonce une g\u00e9n\u00e9ration sacrifi\u00e9e|website=chartsinfrance.net|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[:fr:Le Corbeau (album)|Le Corbeau]]''\n| \n* Released: 21 March 2011\n* Label: Hostile Records, Street Skillz\n* Format: Digital download, CD\n| 3 || 10 || 44\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''E=2MC's''<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with R.E.D.K.)</span>\n| \n* Released: 30 April 2012\n* Label: [[Parlophone]]\n* Format: Digital download, CD\n| 6 || 5 || 27\n|\n* FRA: ~29,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Soprano/news-82041.html|title=Soprano et R.E.D.K d\u00e9voilent le clip \"Simple constat 5\"|website=chartsinfrance.net|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[:fr:Cosmopolitanie|Cosmopolitanie]]''\n| \n* Released: 13 October 2014\n* Label: Parlophone, [[Warner Music Group|Warner Music]], Street Skillz\n* Format: Digital download, CD\n| 2 || 3 || 24\n|\n* FRA: 500,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Soprano/news-105215.html|title=\"L'Everest\" : Soprano passe le cap des 400.000 ventes avec son dernier album|website=chartsinfrance.net|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n|\n* FRA: Diamond\n|-\n! scop